<DESCRIPT>  DESIGN; BOOK  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  FOR contemporary quilters, Eleanor Levie's "Great Little Quilts" (Abrams, 143
pages, $29.95 hard-cover) showcases 45 diminuitive crib quilts made between
1840 and 1940 and provides patterns and directions for duplicating them. And
for Victorian quilt lovers, "Victorian Quilting" (Ballantine, 96 pages, $12.95
softbound) features 30 projects from the Vanessa-Ann Collection, a producer of
needlework kits.;    Contemporary needlepointers can choose from a large crop
of handsomely illustrated how-to books, most of them by British needlework
designers. One of the most beautiful is Elizabeth Bradley's "Decorative
Victorian Needlework" (Clarkson Potter, 168 pages, $32.50 hard-cover), which
features instructions for 25 romantic Victorian-style designs, including
animals, birds and flowers. Most of the projects are available by mail in kit
form, with prices starting at $125.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Peninsula Home  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  BOOKS POINT WAY TO PATTERNS  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Design  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     For the aspiring needlework artist, Julia Barton's "The Art of Embroidery"
(Merehurst/Sterling, 144 pages, $24.95 hard-cover) covers a variety of
needlework techniques, with the emphasis on creating your own designs. In
addition to hand stitchery, Barton discusses machine embroidery, drawing and
painting designs onto fabric, and making textile jewelry.;    Jane Iles'
"Wildflowers in Cross Stitch" (Chronicle, 140 pages, $24.95 hard-cover) offers
detailed instructions for making 23 needlework projects featuring poppies,
primroses and other posies. Jana Hauschild's "Making Gifts in Counted
Cross-Stitch" (St. Martin's Press, 128 pages, $19.95 hard-cover) provides
instructions for more than 100 projects involving various levels of skill; the
emphasis is on folk, nature and holiday motifs. And Shelley Faye Lazar's
"Pictures in Needlework" (Macmillan, 96 pages, $15.95 hard-cover) features a
score of miniature designs suitable for incorporating into a handmade greeting
card or stitching onto a pocket or pillowcase.  </TEXT>
